post_text: Monday, August 12, Pine Level Elementary School (PLES) students received a HUGE surprise. They were introduced to Maggie, PLES’s facility dog. post_text: Third grade students in Mrs. Baxley’s and Mrs. Ferguson’s classes at Prattville Elementary School recently studied plants. Topics of study included the parts of plants, the functions of those parts, the life cycle of plants, and the role of pollinators in the plants’ life cycles. As a culminating project, students utilized Prattville Elementary School’s outdoor classroom planting stations to sow marigold seeds. Students will care for the marigold seedlings in class and then give them as gifts for Mother’s Day in May.

post_text:
The Autauga County Technology Center’s Business Technology Class is home to one of the state’s top Word certification test score holders. As of December, Autauga County Technology Center was the number three school in the state for a student score on a Microsoft Office Word Specialist test, according to Deana Goodwine, Director of Autauga County’s Career Tech program.

This is because of Prattville High School junior Riley Hawkins, who landed a perfect score for Microsoft Office Word 2016. The test is also timed and the fastest perfect scores are ranked based on time used to complete the test. The certification tests given to students are the same ones used for industry certifications. A number of jobs require them, or ask applicants to take a similar test.

Ms. Calhoun is the instructor for the Business Technology Applications class. In this course, Microsoft Office skills are taught to about 100 students each year. Students learn about Microsoft Word, PowerPoint, and Excel. Most students earn certifications in more than one Microsoft program. These Microsoft Certification exams are recognized as Career Readiness Indicators (CRIs) for the state of Alabama.

Business Tech students studied Word through the first semester, and are currently working through PowerPoint and Excel curriculum during the second semester. The Microsoft Office tests demonstrate how teens can succeed in mastering real workplace skills when given the opportunity.

On August 3, 2018, Governor Kay Ivey announced that Billingsley High School has been selected as an official Alabama Bicentennial School. Billingsley School is one of 200 schools selected to receive this special designation and receive a $2,000 grant to fund a project that will allow students to gain an in-depth knowledge of the history of Alabama.

The funds from the grant will provide much needed technology resources for Billingsley students, as well as art supplies. Students will complete project-based learning activities to research historical facts about Alabama. They will use the technology resources to interview Billingsley residents, which will help document the community’s history. Students from various grade levels will create art projects, and community members will be asked to share historical artifacts that Billingsley School will use as part of the school’s display at the Autauga County Bicentennial Fair on November 16-17, 2018.

post_text:
On August 3, 2018, Governor Kay Ivey announced that Pine Level Elementary has been selected as an official Alabama Bicentennial School in a ceremony in the Old House Chamber of the State Capitol. Pine Level Elementary is one of 200 schools selected to receive this special designation and receive a grant to fund a community project developed by the school.
Launched by Governor Ivey in December 2017, the Alabama Bicentennial Schools Initiative encourages all public, private, and homeschool students and teachers to participate in the celebration of Alabama’s 200th anniversary of statehood in 2019. In early 2018, all K-12 schools in Alabama were invited to submit a proposal that engages in outreach and improvement projects to connect their classrooms with their local communities.
From a competitive pool of nearly 400 proposals, 200 schools were selected to be official Alabama Bicentennial Schools and receive $2,000 grants to support the implementation of their projects. Additionally, 56 schools received honorable mentions and $500 grants. Schools were chosen through a review process involving committees of local educators, community leaders, and private citizens.
Representing all corners of the state, the selected schools have developed a wide variety of projects that will make meaningful contributions to their local communities.
Mountains, beaches, lakes, canyons, musicians, artist, inventions, natural resources…the list can go on and on. Alabama is home to many great cities and a variety of rich experiences that many people have never explored. After discussing with administrators and educators, our team felt that the students at Pine Level Elementary needed a sense of understanding of our states geography. The project will consist of a large magnetic map that will be displayed in the front hall of the entrance to Pine Level Elementary. All students will have opportunities throughout the year to interact and learn more about our great state and its many resources. Not only will the map be used for the Bicentennial Celebration but for many years to come. Making connections help students grasp ideas and understand more about their surroundings.
“The Bicentennial Schools Initiative is not only a special way for students to take part in celebrating our 200 years of statehood, but also an opportunity for them to engage within their communities. It fosters a love for the state they call home, and it instills in them the courage to make a difference,” said Governor Ivey.
Mrs. Harry, principal stated , “We are very honored and excited about receiving the grant. Not only do we get to celebrate Alabama’s 200th birthday, but our students and community will learn more about our great state.”
The Alabama Bicentennial Schools Initiative is presented in partnership by Alabama 200, the Alabama Department of Archives and History (ADAH), and the Alabama State Department of Education (ALSDE).
For a complete list of official Bicentennial Schools or for more information, visit www.alabama200.org .

The gifted students at Pine Level Elementary presented a Geography Fair to the students at PLES. The students researched, collaborated, designed, and presented information on a geographical location of their choice where different cultures from across the world and United States were showcased. Students were allowed to grow, understand, and celebrate the fact that we are in a world with many peoples and cultures and develop a sense of self and appreciation of cultural diversity.

Grants from Autauga Education Foundation and Central Alabama Electric were incorporated into the projects that benefited the entire student body. Other resources from the community, such as Boones Chapel, were utilized to help make the fair a success.

The Prattville High School Speech and Debate team competed at the Alabama Speech and Debate Association state tournament February 15-17 at Auburn High School and brought home six state championships, the second most in Prattville school history. Double state champion, Sandu Aladuwaka, won Informative Speaking, After Dinner Speaking and placed second in Domestic Extemporaneous Speaking. Double state champion Holly Griffith won Prose Interpretation and Programmed Interpretation in addition to placing second in the state in Duo. And, finally, Isaac Sherman is the state champion in Novice Senate. The Prattville team was also awarded the Individual Events Sweepstakes Team State Championship for the second year in a row
Other students from Prattville who made it to finals are Luke Clementz, fourth in Novice Senate and semi-finals in Novice Public Forum Debate; Sam Guerrero, fifth in After Dinner Speaking and a quarter-finalist in Novice Public Forum Debate; Grace McKelvey, second in Duo Interp, second in Poetry Interp and second in Programmed Interp; Jack Moore, sixth in Novice Senate and a quarter-finalist in Novice Public Forum Debate; Hannah Murphree, sixth in Prose Interp; Ben Shavers, a semi-finalist in Novice Public Forum and Hugh Sparks, second in International Extemporaneous Speaking and fifth in Informative Speaking. The next tournament for the Prattville team is the Deep South District March 2-3 which is the national qualifying tournament for speech and debate students. The Prattville team is coached by Katy Olienyk and Jordan Berry.

post_text: The Prattville High School Science Olympiad Team competed in the University of Alabama Science Olympiad competition on Saturday, February 24 along with a team from Helena High, Jefferson County International Baccalaureate and three teams from L.A.M.P. and a few others. Under the leadership of head coach Alyson Hahn and assistant Cindy Mitchell, the team made great improvements this year with several top five finishes. Wesley Domsalla and Seth Long finished first in the Material Science and Chemistry Lab events and second in Thermodynamics. Wendy Cho and Aileen Choi finished third in the Forensics event.

post_text:
The Marbury Northstars Marching Band had a successful marching season. Under the direction of David Simpson, the band’s halftime show, Motown Soul, included the hits, Get Ready, I Want You Back, Superstition, Papa Was a Rollin’ Stone, Respect, and When a Man loves a Woman. Mr. Simpson has been a band director for over 25 years and has been at Marbury High School for 15 years. He is also band director at Marbury Middle School. The auxiliary sponsor is Mrs. Kim Hicks. She is the guidance counselor at Marbury High School.

The Northstars began their successful marching season back in July with summer band camp. The students worked extremely hard in the heat of summer to get ready for the marching season. Summer camp concluded with a performance for parents and supporters on July 27th. Meet the Bulldogs on August 12th was the first public performance of the year. The following week began the Marbury Bulldogs football season. The Northstars Marching Band performed at each game, entertaining football fans at home and away. Practices continued after school each week and the band improved their show in preparation for the contest season.

On Saturday, October 7th, the Marbury Northstars attended the Southeastern States Marching Contest held at Troy University. They received all superior ratings in overall band and the following categories: drum major, drumline, color guard and majorettes.

On October 14th, the Northstars traveled to Prattville to attend the Heart of Dixie Band Festival. This contest is a special one for the Marbury Northstars. Back in 1980, the band began competing in marching contest and The Heart of Dixie was the very first contest for the Northstars. Keeping with the winning tradition of the past, the Northstars received all superior ratings for overall band, drumline, color guard and drum major.

On November 4th, alumni of the Northstars band gathered for the first Northstars Alumni Band. Twenty-two alumni members from various years played once again with the Northstars. They played with current members of the Northstars band in the stands. A few were even able to play with their children. This fun event brought back many memories for the alumni and created new memories that will last a lifetime. Once a Northstar, always a Northstar!

The Northstars halftime performances came to an end at the first round playoff game at St. Paul’s in Mobile on November 10th. Mr. Simpson and the students put in many hours of hard work and preparation to make this year a success. The Northstars will march one more time this year in the City of Prattville Christmas Parade on Friday, December 1st.

post_text: Mr. and Miss MHS is chosen solely by the faculty and staff of Marbury High School each year. It is quite an honor to be selected. Mr. and Miss MHS serve as ambassadors for the ideals of Marbury High School. The one senior boy and one senior girl chosen exemplify motivation and hard work and have been successful in all facets of their high school career. Congratulations to this year's Mr. and Miss MHS, Michael Wurtz and Savannah Corbin! Savannah is the daughter of Gene and Kelly Bass. She is currently the President of SGA and National Honor Society. She is the Vice-President of Art Club. Savannah also is an active member of Beta Club, FFA, and Spanish Club. She has been on mission trips to Alaska and Belize with Heritage Baptist Church’s Youth group. Savannah plans to attend college and major in graphic designs. Michael is the son of Joey and Carla Wurtz. He is a member of the Varsity Baseball team. He is a member of Beta Club, Mu Alpha Theta, Spanish Club, and National Honor Society. After he graduates high school, he plans to attend Central Alabama Community College where he has been offered a scholarship to play baseball. Michael wants to further his education and become a veterinarian.

August 29, 2017 at 8:50 AM ·

Last week, Mike Lutzenkirchen, our 2017 Champion of Character, spoke to 7th-12th grade students attending Billingsley High School in Autauga County School System. He talked with them about distracted driving, the importance of unplugging from technology from time to time, the difference between and good friend and a great friend, underage drinking and making better decisions. Mike reminded them, "When you get behind the wheel of a car, you become an adult and have to make adult decisions". The Prattville Autauga Character Coalition was honored to present him with the 2017 Champion of Character Award and to bring him to our community to speak to our youth. #2017ChampionOfCharacter #Lutzie43 #GreatFriend

post_text: Parents, this afternoon we attended a 2:00 EMA meeting and a 3:15 conference call with the Birmingham Weather Service. The Birmingham Weather Service is forecasting 45-50 mph wind gust from 3-7 Monday afternoon. Further discussion revealed ambulances are not safe to respond in 50 mph winds. With the unpredictability of Hurricane Irma, we cannot risk a school bus being on the road Monday afternoon therefore school in Autauga County will be cancelled Monday, September 11, 2017.

post_text: The Prattville Junior High School archery team participated in the National Archery in the Schools National tournament on May 12th in Louisville, Kentucky. The cats represented well, placing 76th out of the 242 middle school teams in attendance from all across the nation. 7th grader Jacob Hollis was the top male shooter for the team with an impressive 280 out of 300 points. At 272, Riley Calhoun was the top female shooter for the team. The group rounded out the season with a team score of 3221 which is their highest score this season and the third highest recorded score in team history. The PJHS team also boasts 20 students who have obtained the title of NASP Academic Archer. This designation indicates that these archers have achieved all A's and B's. The PJHS Archery coaches and the staff of PJHS are very proud of the accomplishments of this group of students.

post_text: Prattville Junior High School (thanks to our Parent Involvement Group) sponsored an assembly for students to #breakbarriers. Coach Casey Nelson from Arlington, Tennessee, spoke to 1,000 students to remind them they can be anything they want to be - as long as they are willing to put in the work. He talked about his life story and inspired our students to break down their barriers. To demonstrate, he did a series of breaks with bricks, etc. The physical demonstration of breaking down the barriers served as a visual reminder that we have to work hard and overcome the mental barriers we have. He addressed work ethic, attitude, and bullying. It was truly an incredible experience for our students! #breakbarriers

post_text: On Tuesday, April 11, 2017, around 200 FFA members from around the state came together to meet with local and state legislators to thank them for their support of Agriculture and Career & Technology Education. After a picture on the state steps, a program was held to include speakers Senator Tom Whatley, Representative David Sessions and Representative Nathaniel Ledbetter. After the program, Marbury FFA members had the chance to receive a personal tour of the House of Representatives Chamber from the Speaker of the House, Mac McCutcheon and Representative Jimmy Martin. FFA members also had the chance to see the Senate Chambers and tour of the State House Grounds. The members enjoyed their time and thank all the legislators for their support and warm welcome.

post_text: Leah Bascomb, Candice Stringfellow, and Alexis Washington reached out to the Birmingham Holocaust Center for their 2017 National History Day project. This year's theme "Taking A Stand" inspired these students to focus on Miep Gies, who stood against the anti-Semitic beliefs of Hitler's Nazi Regime during World War II by hiding Anne Frank and her family. While in Birmingham, Leah, Candice, and Alexis were able to interview Denise Lewis, a second generation Holocaust survivor. The interview was set up by Kendall Chew, the Program's Administrator, who also showed the girls around their museum and gave them access to their archives.

post_text: The Marbury Middle School Junior Beta Club sent thirty-three students to attend the 2017 state convention in Birmingham, Alabama. The students prepared for months to compete in eight team competitions and seventeen individual competitions. Seventh-grader Abby Hall also ran for state vice-president. The club brought back six awards, including the Gold Key Award for club growth. The following awards all earned eligibility to compete at nationals in Orlando, Florida this summer: Mary Beth Hall placed 1st in Handmade Jewelry; Cameron Poe, Jackson Milam, Caleb Sutton, Ricky Gray, and Evan Williamson placed 2nd in Robotics; Zack Johnson placed 3rd in Technology; Eireann Norton placed 3rd in Fiber Arts; and Elena Adams placed 3rd in Sculpture.

post_text: NASP stands for National Archery in the Schools Program. It is a nationwide program that teaches students in grades 4-12 about the sport of archery. Students can compete at region tournaments then advance to state and even national competition. They received a partial grant from Alabama Department of Conservation and Natural Resources to purchase the kit for the students. The kit included 12 Genesis Compound Bows, arrows, 5 targets, arrow net, bow rack and a repair kit. Mrs. Lash is certified as BAI instructor (Basic Archery Instructor) through the NASP program (it was an 8 hour course to become certified). Marbury High School will be competing next year in the regional tournament. Congratulations students and Mrs. Lash!

post_text: On Thursday, January 12, 2017, Marbury High School students got to meet and hear Zeke Pike's story of his rise to stardom in the collegiate football world as a five-star recruit out of high school and his quick fall due to addiction. Pike was slated to be Auburn's starting quarterback straight out of high school, but his addiction to drugs ended his career at Auburn before it began. He was able to play for two other schools, but his addiction took over which ended his college football career. Afterwards, he ended up in a very dark place. His journey back from this place has lead him to speak to high school students across the nation telling his story in hopes that those who listen will not make the same mistakes he did. The students at MHS listened intently to what he had to say. Thank you to Mr. Pike and his father, Mark, for coming to speak and meet with our students! You can learn more information about his speaking engagements at number8ministries.com.

post_text: Marbury High School students gathered together on Thursday, January 5, 2017 for an assembly on Driving Under the Influence. Mr. Dean Argo of the state ABC Board, started the assembly explaining the purpose of the presentation and challenging students to make a pledge to not partake in under-aged drinking or do drugs. He also challenged them to never ever drink while under the influence. Following Mr. Argo, Lt. Steve Adams from the Autauga County Sheriff's Department encouraged students to make wise decisions and let them know what would happen if he or any of his co-workers caught them on the road under the influence. He also explained some of the worst accidents he has come upon have been the result of someone driving under the influence. This led into Mrs. Bethany Chancellor's story. Mrs. Chancellor is from the MADD (Mothers Against Drunk Driving) organization. Students were very attentive as she recounted her tragic story of being involved in an accident with a drunk driver. Four years ago just a few miles north of Autauga County in Jemison, Alabama, Mrs. Chancellor, her husband, and two boys were hit head on by a drunk driver. The accident killed her husband and severely injured her oldest child. She reminded students that the driver's one poor choice had an effect on way more people than just himself. Dr. Bill Day, from the Alabama Citizen's Action Program then showed pictures of people who were innocent victims and how their life was changed because of the poor decision of another. The program concluded with Mrs. Mandy Johnson from District Attorney Randall Houston's office. She explained the reality of the situation for young people who are prosecuted for under-aged drinking and driving under the influence. There are no passes, and if students are involved in accidents that seriously injure or kill another person as a result of driving under the influence, the consequences are even greater.

post_text:
Autauga County Technology Center announced today that they have awarded 54 Microsoft Office Specialist (MOS) Word certifications, an industry-recognized, standards-based credential for validating Microsoft Office skills. Two students made a perfect score.
Microsoft Office Specialist Certification gives students the tools to build a brighter future. It not only enhances academic performance but also provides students with a substantial advantage in their higher learning and workforce pursuits.
“Students will begin working on certification in Excel when we return in January,” said Mrs. Goldman, IT Academy instructor. “The students are excited and looking forward to earning their next credential.” Students in the ACTC IT Academy classes will have the opportunity to earn a third credential in PowerPoint this spring.

post_text: Marbury High School students attended a special Veterans’ Day Program on the afternoon of Thursday, November 10, 2016. This program, put together by MHS English teacher Mrs. Leslie Morgan, involved many students. To begin, Mrs. Donna Finch, Principal of Marbury High School, called the assembly to order. The Marbury High School JROTC presented and posted the colors while the Marbury High School North Stars Band played the National Anthem. Junior Abby Douglas then sang an acoustic version of "God Bless America." After Abby's performance, the band continued the program by playing the "Armed Forces Medley." Mrs. Morgan asked that students, teachers, and faculty members stand whenever the song for their branch of service was played. Mrs. Morgan then introduced Major Don Neal, retired United States Marine Core officer, and the keynote speaker for the day. Major Neal spoke to the students about his time of service and the importance of our current military service men and women. Once Major Neal finished, the band played Lee Greenwood's "God Bless the U.S.A." followed by a moment of silence and the playing of "Taps" for all those who made the ultimate sacrifice in service to our country. Thank you to all who participated and to our students who showed such great respect during the entire ceremony.

post_text: Marbury Middle School Beta Club welcomed 78 new members after the first nine weeks of school, making their club a total of 110 students. Before the Thanksgiving break, they had their first meeting with the new members and started the first service project with the new members, the Adopt-a-Mile program. All members spent over an hour picking up trash on County Road 20 and on the school campus. This photo was taken after the service project was complete. They have several service projects going on during December. The MMS Beta Club will be participating in Toys for Tots, putting together holiday hope chests for local foster children, and making "cookies in a jar" for local senior citizens.

post_text: The ACTC partnered with the Prattville Chamber of Commerce, AIDT, ATN, Lincoln Electric, Central Alabama Electric Cooperative, Central Alabama Community College, Marbury Steel, International Paper, Tenaska and Gipson’s Tire Pros to allow high school students to participate in hands-on activities related to manufacturing careers. During the Manufacturing Career Day event, the ACTC held a panel discussion for students about manufacturing and careers available in local manufacturing facilities and businesses in the area needing a skilled labor force. Afterwards, students toured simulations and Mobile Training Units at the Technology Center. This event was held to draw attention to manufacturing’s present-day reality and encourages our students to develop the skills they need to qualify for long-term careers in this secure and growing sector of the economy and helping to ensure our graduates are college or career ready when they graduate.

post_text:
Students at Autaugaville and Billingsley Schools are participating in the 21st annual “Symbolic Monarch Butterfly Migration” with students across North America. Over 60,000 students in the United States and Canada created symbolic butterflies and mailed them to Mexico. Children at the sanctuaries in Mexico will take care of them this winter and send them back north in the spring. You can follow the journey by visiting http://www.learner.org/jnorth/maps/symbolic_fall2016.html.
While our students are helping to build the monarch population by planting milkweed and reporting our sightings, the monarch is in turn providing an authentic lesson on communication, conservation, and ambassadorship.

post_text: On June 23, 2016, The State of Alabama filed a resolution commending the Autauga County school health nurses for exemplary service while caring for the health needs of students while they are in the school setting. It resolved that the Autauga County school nurses are most highly honored and commended for the health care services they provide for the children in the schools in Alabama. At the regular board meeting on September 22, 2016, the nurses were recognized for this outstanding accomplishment. A big THANKS to our nurses for everything they do to care for the students in Autauga County schools.
